climbs.name: Wake of the Flood aka Challenges of Leisure
climbs.fa: FA: Bob Horan, 1997; FFA: Bob Horan with Jim Ghiselli, Spring 1999? Jim Redo?

content.description: This route is 13 bolts long, has a slab crux, has really small holds. Don't do it in the sun. It is good climbing.
content.protection: This was previously known as "Wake Of The Flood" but was renamed. It was an abandoned project. It is 13 bolts long! It has a slab crux, but the route overall does not really climb like a slab. Killer, go do it.
content.location:
The route is just right of

Sargasso Sea

.

content.description:
Start in the same spot as

Shiny Toys

, at the bottom of a black streak. Head right after the small roof, then follow the crack for 10' to a no-hands rest. Continue up and right to a stance in a clean scoop. Work through the crux to the easier section above.

It has good feet most of the way.
content.protection: Pitons and bolts and a 2-bolt anchor with rap rings.
content.location: This is on the right side of Oceanic Wall, 15' up and right after it bends away from the creek.

content.description:
Start on

Black Lagoon

, and traverse straight right past two pins about 25 feet off the deck.  Traverse past the adjacent 11d, and climb the finger cracks to the left of

Shiny Toys

.  After gaining the next horizontal, traverse left to thin crack and one bolt.  Lower off

Black Lagoon

or the 11d to the right.
content.protection: Gear to #1 with emphasis on small stuff....
content.location:
Start and finish with

Creature from the Black Lagoon

....

content.description: This route is on the far right-hand side of Oceanic Wall (up the ramp a little towards Dream Dome). It follows a blackened stripe of rock. Look for a piton about 15 feet up and two bolts just above the roof. The crux is pulling the roof. Work left after the roof to the two-bolt anchor.
content.protection: This is a mixed gear & bolt route, bring a standard rack. There are two bolts and a piton to a double bolt anchor.

climbs.name: Shiek Yer Bouti
climbs.fa: Steve Sangdahl, Janet Robinson, and John Baldwin

content.description:
This route is located on the right side of Oceanic Wall.

Begin in a an A-shaped roof with a bolt just off the ground.  Pull the roof via a technical and powerful 11.d move with  good protection from the bolt (crux). Continue up past another bolt to two fixed pins, equalize these and continue up into a thin left angling seam, 11.a. Clip another bolt, pull another 11d move and meet up with Twistin' by the Pool where you will find some tricky 5.10 moves about 15 feet above an old fixed pin, a wee bit spicy.

Anchor at 85'.
content.protection: 8 draws and something for the 2 bolt anchor.

content.description: The route begins with a bang- an obvious side pull sets you up for throw to better holds. From this move, climb into a strenous seam that spits you out onto the slab. Balance and smear your way    through the crux and onto to easier climbing.
content.protection: Bring draws for 9 bolts and a two bolt anchor.

content.description:
This route is right of the two new routes (

Pound Town

and the unnamed DH line) on the far right side of Oceanic Wall.  This climbs the thin and dirty crack just right of Dan's new line.  The crack leads to a shelf (poor gear) and continues up above, eventually meeting up with the last bolt and anchors on Dan's new route.  This is not a great route, but I thought I should add it to MP for completeness.
content.protection: Falling is not recommended.  I placed thin DMM offsets below the shelf.  Good finger size pieces protect the top nicely.
content.location: This is the farthest right climb on Oceanic Wall.

content.description:
On the far right of Oceanic Wall, there are currently 3 routes. Pound Town is the second route left of the corner (where

Wrinkles In Time

starts) through a sculpted water streak. Climb up ledges on good holds, then move into face climbing with jugs and edges. Execute the crux around the 4th bolt, then continue on stellar rock to the chains.
content.protection: 7 draws; mussy hooks for anchor.
content.location: This is the second bolted route from the left of the corner. It goes through a sculpted water streak.

climbs.name: Pla Pwy (Sick Fish)
climbs.fa: Jonas Wallin, Josh Lyons, Zac Holtzman

content.description:
Sick Fish shares the same start as

Creatures From The Black Lagoon

and Twisting By The Pool. Instead of climbing the diagonal crack follow the line of titanium bolts straight up the face. Climb over a small roof to a low angle face. The route meets up with

Mud Shark

after the fifth bolt. Finish on the top bit of

Mud Shark

.
content.protection:
Ten bolts. Five titanium glue-in bolts on Sick Fish and five expansion bolts after meeting up with the top part of

Mud Shark

. Three bolt anchor.
content.location:
This is on the Oceanic Wall between

Mud Shark

and

Creatures From The Black Lagoon

. Rappel or lower off from the anchors on

Mud Shark

. The easiest way to find the route is locate the line of titanium glue-in bolts. We used Hilti RE-500 glue which has a pink or red color to it.

content.description:
Start just left of

Shiny Toys

. Place small cams (TCUs/Aliens) and nuts up to a cruxy bolt-protected overhang. Pull the overhang, and join easier rock on

Shiny Toys

to the anchor with chains.
content.protection: Small cams (Aliens/TCUs/X4s), 0.75-2" cams (optional for easier climbing above the crux), nuts, draws, and some shoulder length slings.
content.location:
This is in between

Shiek Yer Bouti

and

Shiny Toys

.

climbs.name: Mud Shark
climbs.fa: Steve Sangdahl and John Baldwin, 1996 or 1997

content.description:
Pretty fun steep slab climbing.  Begin as for

Dream On

and

Leviathan

in the center of the wall.  Climb the three bolt 5.10a to the 2 bolt anchor.  Mud Shark takes the rightmost of the three bolted lines above the anchor.

Climb the weird seam to a crux traverse sequence below a bulge...funky and slippery.  4 or 5 bolts past the anchor...8 or 9 total.
content.protection: 8 or 9 QDS and 2 bolt anchor.

content.description:
Climb

Dream Come True

to below the 5th bolt, and veer right.
content.protection: 6 bolts and a fixed nut.
content.location:
This is the rightward finish of

Dream Come True

.

climbs.name: Leviathan
climbs.fa: FA: Richard Rossiter and Gail Effron, 1996. FFA: Steve Sangdahl and John Baldwin

content.description: This route starts from the center of Oceanic Wall and climbs 30 feet of 10a terrain before bypassing a two-bolt anchor and ascending left and up on more difficult rock for another 45 feet. The steep section just after the first anchor is especially thoughtful and fun.
content.protection: 3 bolts to a 2 bolt anchor, then 4 more to another 2 bolts.

content.description:
This was at one time the leftmost route on Oceanic Wall, but there is now at least one other route further left. In the Rossiter guide it says, "To be bolted", so apparently at the time the guidebook was written this climb had not been bolted or lead.

Start left of

The Deep

below a shallow, A-shaped ceiling. The first bolt is maybe 15 feet up, but getting there is relatively easy with positive holds. Climb through the apex of the roof, move a bit left through a bulge and up to a short crack. The moves up the crack, using holds either left or right of the crack (or both) are hard and lead to a small stance at the crux. The next clip (if you're not really tall) is either difficult off of treacherous footholds, or you have to do the crux a few feet about the previous bolt and then make an easy clip. The crux moves involve some thin feet smears off of laybacks. Undercling up and right and make a long reach to a jug which is the left end of the ledge that angles up and left from

The Deep

. Join

The Deep

for the fun upper wall. The upper face is a bit runout but very secure due to big knobs where you need them.
content.protection:
Approximately 10 bolts to a 2-bolt anchor with rings. Bring a few extra draws, since I didn't count  the bolts.

Per

Carl Schaefer

: there are 7 bolts and 2 anchor bolts (one is just hangers without rings or chains).

content.description: Delicate, balancey, technical - this route tests your ability to find and stand up on tiny nibs while palming, pinching, or pulling on only slightly larger knobs and edges. The crux section is between bolts 4-9; enjoy figuring out when to be on which side of the bolt line.
content.protection: 10 bolts to a 2-bolt anchor.
content.location:
This is the 2nd bolted line from the left, followed by a wide, dirty section, and then

In Your Dreams

.

This is described in the 2017 D'Antonio guidebook as "The letmost [sic] bolted line"

content.description: Start sitting under the overhang and squeeze out the obvious prow. A different sequence has been climbed without the prow slopers.
content.protection: A Mondo and a Drop Zone should do ya.
content.location: This is on the opposite side of the creek from the Oceanic Wall.

content.description: This route starts from the center of Oceanic Wall, and climbs 30 feet of easy terrain before bypassing a two-bolt anchor and ascending left as for Leviathon for ~15 feet before breaking right again and climbing a right-leaning lieback feature. Shares an anchor with Leviathon.
content.protection: Fully bolted. You can lower from the anchor with a 50m rope.

climbs.name: Dream Come True
climbs.fa: John Baldwin and Steve Sangdahl. Sept. 1, 1997

content.description: The crux is around the third bolt. A thin, leaning seam with face holds.  Finish to the left. Right-hand finish is Nightmare Come True, also 5.12a.
content.protection: 5 bolts.
content.location:
Climb

Creature From The Black Lagoon

to its anchor, ascend an easy bit to the big ledge, and a two bolt anchor with chains. Above is an overhanging headwall.

climbs.name: The Deep
climbs.fa: Richard Rossiter and Leah Macaluso, June 1996.

content.description: This route is diverse. It begins with a delicate mantle that leads into a more powerful roof. Beyond    the roof is nice rest stance. Use it, and then negotiate the crux with small holds and high step move. The    rest of the route turns into easy slab climbing, with protection becoming more sparse.
content.protection:
You'll need quickdraws for 10 bolts and a two-bolt anchor.

Per

Dan Raymond

: this has its own anchors.

climbs.name: Creature from the Black Lagoon
climbs.fa: Steve Sangdahl, Janet Robinson, and John Baldwin

content.description: An easy start leads to the thin and tricky undercling / lieback crux of this route at ~40 feet. The route is distinguished by an obvious black waterstreak, located on the right side of the wall.
content.protection: This is fully bolted. You can lower from the anchor with a 60m rope. There are 11 bolts to a 2 bolt anchor.

content.description:
The route directly to the right of

Pound Town

.  Start out with bolts leading up to the left side of the ledge with a tree.  Clip two more bolts then step right to utilize twin cracks, place bomber nuts.  Clip one last bolt to the chains.

NOTE: this may be just a temporary name until Dan Hare decides the REAL name....
content.protection: 6 bolts plus two medium to large nuts. A 0.5 cam placement is available also. Most people will be totally fine with one large nut. There are anchors with rings (now with Mussy hooks).
content.location: This is to the left of the corner that head to the left side of the ledge with a tree.

content.description:
Belie Black looks dirtier than it climbs, but it is an enjoyable warm-up. Start right of a right-facing corner (with a tree on top), climb up over a small roof, and lieback your way to the anchor.

I am documenting a pre-existing route. Anyone with FA or original name info, click "Improve This Page" above.
content.protection: Seven bolts to a 2-bolt anchor (Mussy hooks).
content.location: At the far left end of Oceanic Wall, this [was] the leftmost bolted line.
